---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---
<Base title="What is llms.txt?" description="Learn about llms.txt — the new standard for telling AI models about your website. Spec explainer, best practices, and how to create one.">
  <article class="learn-page">
    <div class="container content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/learn/llms-txt">Learn</a> / <span>llms.txt</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>What is llms.txt?</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        <strong>llms.txt</strong> is a proposed standard (created by Jeremy Howard, Sept 2024) that gives AI language models
        structured information about your website. Think of it as a README for AI — it tells models what your site does,
        what's important, and where to find key content.
      </p>

      <section>
        <h2>Why does it matter?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>AI models are already reading your site.</strong> ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, and others browse the web. Without llms.txt, they guess what your site is about.</li>
          <li><strong>Control the narrative.</strong> llms.txt lets you tell AI exactly what you want it to know — your tagline, key pages, documentation structure.</li>
          <li><strong>Better AI search results.</strong> Sites with llms.txt may get more accurate representation in AI-powered search engines.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Format</h2>
        <p>llms.txt is a simple Markdown-like text file placed at <code>/llms.txt</code> on your domain root.</p>
        <pre><code># Your Site Name

> A brief description of what your site does.

## Docs

- [Getting Started](https://example.com/docs/getting-started): Quick start guide
- [API Reference](https://example.com/docs/api): Full API documentation

## Blog

- [Latest Release](https://example.com/blog/v2): What's new in v2</code></pre>

        <h3>Structure rules</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Title (required):</strong> First line must be <code># Your Site Name</code></li>
          <li><strong>Description (recommended):</strong> A blockquote or paragraph after the title</li>
          <li><strong>Sections (recommended):</strong> Use <code>## Section Name</code> headings to organize links</li>
          <li><strong>Links (recommended):</strong> Markdown links with descriptions: <code>[Title](URL): Description</code></li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Best Practices</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Keep it concise — under 50KB. AI models have context limits.</li>
          <li>Lead with your most important pages (docs, pricing, getting started).</li>
          <li>Use descriptive link text, not "click here" or raw URLs.</li>
          <li>Serve as <code>text/plain</code> or <code>text/markdown</code> content type.</li>
          <li>Update when you ship major changes to your site structure.</li>
          <li>Consider also creating <code>llms-full.txt</code> for comprehensive documentation.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Who's using it?</h2>
        <p>
          Major sites and frameworks are adopting llms.txt including Anthropic (docs.anthropic.com),
          Cloudflare, Stripe, and many open source projects. The spec is gaining traction as
          AI-powered search becomes mainstream.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>How It Relates to Other Files</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Audience</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>robots.txt</strong></td><td>Control which bots can crawl</td><td>All crawlers</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>llms.txt</strong></td><td>Tell AI what your site is about</td><td>AI language models</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>ai.txt</strong></td><td>AI usage policy & permissions</td><td>AI companies</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>sitemap.xml</strong></td><td>List all pages for indexing</td><td>Search engines</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <h3>Check your site</h3>
        <p>See if you have an llms.txt and how it scores.</p>
        <a href="/" class="action-btn action-btn-primary">Scan your domain</a>
        <a href="/tools/generator/llms-txt" class="action-btn action-btn-secondary">Generate llms.txt</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
